[[Region Select]] <<regionCode>><<sectionheader "The South Pacific">> !!Regional Pre-Departure Orientation: The South Pacific <<sidebar>>You’ve selected the South Pacific region. //If this is not where you'll be traveling, <<return "go back">> and try again!//<</sidebar>> The South Pacific is a region that encompasses a lot of islands—more than 25,000! Even though the region covers a lot of area, it has the smallest land area (read: it’s mostly ocean), and the second smallest population of the continents (only Antarctica has fewer). Because of the mostly-ocean situation, thoughts of South Pacific conjure palm trees, blue seas, maybe a hammock, but we’re here to tell you that, unfortunately… Just kidding. It’s a paradise! But it’s also full of super cosmopolitan cities and developed economies, along with remote villages and indigenous traditions. The mix of cultures in the South Pacific includes Polynesian, Micronesian, Melanesian, Austronesion, and so many more. More diverse than even the myriad of cultures are the languages! From the tiniest islands to the biggest (Australia), travelers in the South Pacific experience a range from English to Spanish to French to hundreds of indigenous languages. Bottom line: South Pacific sounds like one place, but really it is many, and your study abroad experience will allow you a just a window into what this region has to offer. <<map>><<sectionheader "Academic Policies">> !!!What does this mean for me? OK, so what do these academic policies actually mean for your time abroad? Let's boil them down: *Put in the effort to succeed academically. Even though the grades you earn won’t factor into your GPA, ''they will still show up'' in the external section of your transcript. *If you’re on a semester-long program and the total credits you earn abroad amounts to fewer than 12 VU credits, you will be placed on ''academic probation'', and your financial aid eligibility may be in jeopardy. *You need to deal with grade and course registration questions while you are abroad. Don't try to resolve them back at Vanderbilt. ''VU can’t change your grades'' or remove courses from your transcript. *Take advantage of tutoring and other academic support abroad. *Be aware of your study abroad program’s academic regulations--and follow them! Be especially careful with absence and illness policies. *Make sure to drop any courses you don’t want to take during your program’s official drop/add period. <<button[[Check Your Knowledge|Intro to Quizzes]]>><</button>> <<set $sidebar = "blank">><<question "You earned a C in ECON 2100 at Vanderbilt. One of the courses on your abroad program is equivalent to ECON 2100, so you can take that and improve your grade.">>\ \ <<if $Academic1 is "complete">>\ <<sidebar>>You have already completed this section of questions! Click below to skip this quiz module. <<button [[Skip|SA Course Review]]>><</button>><</sidebar>><</if>><<sectionheader "Academic Policies">> !!Study Abroad Course Review Let’s say you plan to take Management Accounting while at the University of Sydney. How will this course count at Vanderbilt and how will it be reflected on your degree audit? The answer is… ''Study Abroad Course Review!'' To earn Vanderbilt credit, each course you take abroad needs to be evaluated by Vanderbilt faculty. This process determines how the course will count at Vanderbilt—''or if it will count at all''. Lucky for you, every course Vanderbilt students have taken abroad in the last five years can be seen on the ''YES Study Abroad Course Search Tool''. <<button[[Continue|YES SA Course Search Tool]]>><</button>> <<set $complete = "yes">><<sectionheader "Action Items">> <img style="height:300px;" class="aniview" data-av-animation="slideInRight" src="https://vugeo.github.io/regional/humaaans/flat assets/Humaaans/standing-8.png"> <img style="height:300px;" src="https://vugeo.github.io/regional/humaaans/flat assets/Humaaans/standing-26.png"> <img style="height:290px;" src="https://vugeo.github.io/regional/humaaans/flat assets/Humaaans/standing-27.png"> ! Whenever you see an Action Item screen, you are encouraged to complete that task //right now!// Later, you'll also have access to a complete checklist of Action Items that you can come back to any time. Ready for your first Action Item?</div> <p class="continue-button" style="text-align:center"><<button [[Continue|Bookmark Resilient Traveling and Inclusion Resources]]>><</button>></p> \<<sectionheader "Academic Policies">> !!Vanderbilt Registration A few months after you commit to your program, GEO registers you into a ''placeholder course'' for your term abroad. The placeholder ensures that while studying abroad, you remain registered at Vanderbilt. This registration allows you to access Vanderbilt financial aid, as well as systems that let you, for example, register for the next term’s classes, log in to YES and other applications, utilize safety resources, and access campus services including online library resources and the University Counseling Center. If you've registered yourself for classes on campus, GEO won't be able to register you in your placeholder. ''Be sure to withdraw from your on-campus courses!'' <<button [[Next|Registration (2)]]>><</button>><<sectionheader "Academic Policies">> !!Academics Let’s get some basic logistics squared away, to prepare you to focus on the actual learning and the fun part of studying abroad. !!!Policies on Credits and Grades *Credits you earn on programs offered through GEO are a special type of course credit called Study Abroad/Away Credit (SAC). ''SAC fulfill major/minor requirements and satisfy on-campus residency requirements.'' *SAC is separate from transfer credit and ''doesn't count toward university, college, or departmental transfer credit limit.'' *The grades you earn will be reflected on your Vanderbilt transcript but ''not factored into your cumulative GPA.'' *You ''cannot'' take courses pass/fail while abroad. *Just as at Vanderbilt, ''you must take the equivalent of 12 to 18 hours of credit''--except in the summer, of course. In the summer, you’ll come back with as many credits as you earn in the courses you take. <<deepdive "https://vugeo.github.io/regional/humaaans/flat assets/Humaaans/sitting-2.png">> !!!! How will this affect medical school applications? When applying to medical school, AMCAS, the application service used by most US medical schools, will include grades from Vanderbilt-approved study abroad programs <<linkreplace "...(Read more)" t8n>>in its own GPA calculation, because AMCAS generally recognizes study abroad credit transferred to a US university as credit that should count toward the AMCAS GPA. Essentially, the Vanderbilt transcript will list US equivalents for all grades and credit hours earned on VU-approved study abroad programs, even though VU isn’t counting these grades in its own GPA calculation. ''AMCAS will then pick up those US grades/credits and include them in the AMCAS GPA calculation.'' So- be sure to work hard in your abroad courses! You can review AMCAS’s own description of this procedure, as well as instructions for students AMCAS application, on [[AMCA’s website|https://students-residents.aamc.org/applying-medical-school/applying-medical-school-process/applying-medical-school-amcas/]]. If you have other questions, contact the [[Health Professions Advisory Office|https://www.vanderbilt.edu/hpao/]]. <</linkreplace>><</deepdive>> That said, study abroad courses also come with a number of special rules. <<button[[Continue|Review Academic Policies]]>> <</button>><<sectionheader "Fees, Cost, and Billing">> Vanderbilt will bill you for the ''basic costs'' (i.e. tuition, program fee, study abroad administrative fee) for your program. The Budget Sheets available on [[GEO's website|https://vanderbilt.edu/geo/finances/budget-sheets/]] or later in this presentation show exactly what is covered in the Program Fee charged by VU. Be aware that there are ''out-of-pocket costs'' that are not billed by Vanderbilt—including airfare, visa fees, and more—which you should factor into your overall budget. These are estimated on your GEO Budget Sheet, and should be considered as you make your plans. Out-of-pocket costs will be considered by the Office of Financial Aid if you [[review your study abroad|https://forms.vanderbilt.edu/view.php?id=840651]] with them. <<sidebar "What's in My Vanderbilt Bill?">> \ *Vanderbilt Tuition: Academic costs of the program *Program Fee: Non-academic costs, e.g. housing.* *Study Abroad Administrative Fee: Covers mandatory international health insurance from Vanderbilt's provider. <nowiki>*</nowiki> A very small number of study abroad programs have academic costs that exceed the cost of Vanderbilt tuition. Academic costs exceeding VU tuition are added to the Program Fee.<</sidebar>> <<button [[Next|Fees, Cost, and Billing (2)]] >><</button>><div id="advisors"></div>[[See all advisors|https://vanderbilt.edu/geo/advising/#staffadvisors]] <div id ="ui-bar-print"><span class="print"><a href="javascript:window.print()"><img alt="print" style="width:25px;height:25px" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/vu-wp0/wp-content/uploads/sites/234/2018/07/26132613/128x128.png"></a></span></div> <div id="contactAdv"><span class="advisor"><a target="_blank" href="https://www.vanderbilt.edu/geo/advising/">[img[https://vugeo.github.io/regional/ui/person-adv.png]]</a></span></div> <div id="bookmarksButton"><span class="bookmarkButton"><<link "Bookmarks">><<script>>UI.saves();document.getElementById("ui-dialog-title").textContent = "Bookmarks";<</script>><</link>></span></div> <div id="portalButton"><span class="portal hidden"><<link [img[https://vugeo.github.io/regional/ui/portal-128x128.png]]>><<goto "End Portal">><</link>></span></div> <<if $complete is "yes">><<removeclass ".portal" "hidden">><</if>><<answer "false" "False. Here are a few differences you might notice at universities in the South Pacific: *''Larger class size'': less individual attention means you will be responsible for ensuring you understand the material and asking for help if you need it *''More focus on exams'': grades are heavily weighted towards mid-term and final rather than on work throughout the semester *''Different grading style'': you will be graded up from zero rather than marks off from 100 Details of academic culture will vary by institution; [[program alumni|https://vanderbilt.edu/geo/advising/#alumni]] are your best resource to get a sense of what to expect. Here are some examples of what they had to say: <div class="quote">//The classes were challenging but there was much less busy work than in my classes at Vandy. Lectures…are recorded which is extremely helpful for studying. However, it can make it easy to fall behind if you aren’t disciplined.// – IFSA University of Queensland Alum</div> <div class="quote">//Simply put, there is significantly less amount of work overall, but if you don't do well on the few assignments you are given you will fail the class as there is not much leeway.// – University of Melbourne Alum</div> <div class="quote">//Finals are worth a very large percentage of your grade, and if you fail the final you automatically fail the class. Papers are graded much more harshly than at Vandy.// – IFSA University of Queensland Alum</div> <div class="quote">//Even though the grading scale is easier, the engineering courses are much harder.// – IFSA University of Canterbury Alum</div> <div class="quote">//SIT was incredibly different from Vanderbilt because it is an experiential learning model. The work was not so much about the content, but more how we reflected on what we were learning and tied it to the big picture themes of the courses.// – SIT Samoa Alum</div> <<sidebar>>''SIT programs'' all follow a distinctive model. The ''coursework is frontloaded'' and the ''final month is dedicated to an Independent Study Project (ISP) or an Internship''. These ISPs and internships offer a unique opportunity to explore your academic interest within the local cultural context. Experiential learning is at the core of the SIT experience – so expect courses to be ''reflective, interactive, and hands-on''. Much of your learning will take place outside of the classroom through field trips, interactions with locals, guest seminars, homestay experience, group travel, etc. ''The more you engage and reflect, the more you will take away from your program''. Given the ''highly structured'' program model, you will have little latitude to conduct independent travel, but traveling before or after the program is an option. Given the particularity of the SIT program locations, ''curfews may be imposed'' for safety and security. <</sidebar>><<sectionheader "Academic Policies">> !!Transcripts After you return from abroad, your program will send the Vanderbilt University Registrar a final transcript. The University Registrar will translate the grades, if needed, into their US equivalents. This information will then replace the placeholder on your Vanderbilt transcript--but ''//only//'' if you all your course reviews are complete. Institutions abroad have their own schedules for reporting grades and producing transcripts. This typically takes one to two months, but in extreme cases, up to six months. ''Only your program or host institution can expedite the reporting of your grades to VU''. Some programs require you to say where they should send your transcript. It’s not all shrimps on the barbie, mate! <iframe style="text-align:center;" width="560" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/-oLlOluxx78" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture" allowfullscreen></iframe> Australia was actually first settled as a [[penal colony|https://www.nytimes.com/2011/01/02/travel/02sydney.html]] by Great Britain after the US stopped accepting Britain’s convicts. Today, Australia is a wealthy and multicultural country that benefits from immigration: [[more than one in four Australian residents was born outside of Australia, and many more are first- or second-generation Australians|https://www.buzzfeed.com/annamendoza/all-the-colours-of-the-world]]. Australia has many deadly animals- the saltwater crocodile, great white shark, tons of snakes- but as a city-dweller, ''you need not be too concerned''. However, it can’t hurt to take a look at some of the [[well-known Australian predators...|https://www.thrillist.com/travel/nation/things-in-australia-that-will-kill-you-animals-that-will-try-to-kill-you]] Don’t worry, Australia is mostly full of beaches, rainforest, and desert, and vineyards, and oh yeah that little-known natural wonder of the world, the Great Barrier Reef. Add in some of the [[most liveable cities|http://www.cnn.com/2016/08/18/travel/most-livable-city-2016/]] in the world, and you might never want to leave! But you don’t have to take our word for it... <iframe width="560" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/jys8lhutwkI" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture" allowfullscreen></iframe> <<deepdive "https://vugeo.github.io/regional/humaaans/flat assets/Humaaans/sitting-2.png">> Want to keep learning about Australia? Read more [[here|https://culturalatlas.sbs.com.au/australian-culture/australian-culture-core-concepts]] (via [[Cultural Atlas|https://culturalatlas.sbs.com.au/]]).<</deepdive>><<set $country to "New Zealand">><<sectionheader "New Zealand">> <<sidebar>><img class="sidebar-flag aniview" data-av-animation="tada" src="https://vugeo.github.io/regional/flags/nz.png">You’ve selected New Zealand. //If this is not where you'll be traveling, <<return "go back">> and try again!//<</sidebar>> New Zealand is a small country that packs a big (and beautiful!) punch. But definitely not too small to be left off the map! <iframe width="560" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/HynsTvRVLiI" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture" allowfullscreen></iframe> New Zealanders are called ''Kiwis'' (derived from their national bird, not the fruit!) Kiwis invented bungee-jumping, frozen meat, and electric fences, and while they didn’t invent rugby, they did make it <<linkappend "a lot more interesting." t8n>> <iframe width="560" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/yiKFYTFJ_kw" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture" allowfullscreen></iframe><</linkappend>> ''Tramping'' (hiking) is a popular activity in New Zealand, and one of the most revered Kiwis is Sir Edmund Hillary, the first person to climb Mt. Everest. Between its LOTR-worthy landscapes, distinctive Maori culture, and one of the best education systems in the world, New Zealand is a special place to study abroad. And we guarantee that you will come back with at least a dozen sheep photos in your cameral roll. //Kia Ora//! <img src="http://vugeo.github.io/regional/images/new-zealand-whangaparosa.jpg" style="width:80ch;"> <<sidebar>>Don’t be surprised to see people barefoot- at the airport, restaurants, the grocery store- it’s very common in NZ!<</sidebar>> <<deepdive "https://vugeo.github.io/regional/humaaans/flat assets/Humaaans/sitting-2.png">>Want to keep learning about New Zealand? Read more [[here|https://culturalatlas.sbs.com.au/new-zealand-culture/new-zealand-culture-core-concepts#new-zealand-culture-core-concepts]] (via [[Cultural Atlas|https://culturalatlas.sbs.com.au/]]).<</deepdive>><<set $country to "Samoa">><<sectionheader "Samoa">> <<sidebar>><img class="sidebar-flag aniview" data-av-animation="tada" src="https://vugeo.github.io/regional/flags/ws.png">You’ve selected Samoa. //If this is not where you'll be traveling, <<return "go back">> and try again!//<</sidebar>> Samoa (pronounced SA-mo-wa) is the first independent Polynesian nation, and consists of two big islands and eight smaller islands located roughly equidistant from the United States and New Zealand. ''Samoa is not to be confused with American Samoa'', which is a nearby set of islands controlled by the US. As a language, Samoan is similar to Hawaiian, Tongan, Tahitian, Maori, and other Polynesian languages. <<sidebar>><b><a target="_blank" href="https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/the-meaning-of-the-word-covfefe-in-the-samoan-language_us_592f0f0ae4b017b267edff7e">The Meaning Of The Word ‘Covfefe’ In The Samoan Language</a></b><</sidebar>> In Samoan culture most activities are ''done together'', and people will often live within one room in their //fale// (house). This is just one of [[many differences|https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/73226994/null]] between western, European influenced daily life and Samoan daily life. ''Tattooing'' is also an important part of Samoan culture--you will often see men tattooed from mid-back down to the knees, and women from the thigh to just below the knee. One famous Samoan descendant and his Polynesian tattoos: Dwayne ‘The Rock’ Johnson. Samoan tattoos communicated information on social status, ancestry, religion, age, and much more. <<sidebar>>''What Does Dwayne’s Polynesian Tattoo Mean?'' (retrieved from [[Memory Lane Tattoo|http://www.memorylane.tattoo/blog-2133823458/dwayne-johnson-the-rock-tattoos]]) <img style="width:40ch; float:right; margin:25px;" src="http://vugeo.github.io/regional/images/dwayne-johnson-diagram.jpg">A) These are coconut leaves, or niu, which denote a Samoan chief-warrior. B) This is the sun which brings good fortune. C) This isa/ga fa’atasi (three people in one), That’s me with my arms open. As it continues on my chest, it connects to my o lo’u to’a/ua (my wife, Dany) and my o lo’u afafine (my daughter, Simone Alexandra). D) These descending swirls represent past, present and future, with the future becoming ever bigger. The pattern continues under my arm, where its meaning is written: “It changes in the place where it is found to be gone.” E) These two eyes, called o mata e lua, represent my ancestors watching over my path. F) This is the Great Eye, It’s an intimidating symbol that allows its user to possess the spirit of his enemy. The eye is used to distract the enemy in a confrontation. G) This broken face, marked by shark teeth—a symbol of strength—is my spirit protector and a symbol of my struggle. H) This is the priest and spiritual guide, who raises a warrior to enlightenment and supernatural power under the eyes of the warrior’s ancestors. I) These are stones of achievement and abundance. They’re the foundation of my life and symbols of my dedication. They bring the right to stand and speak with honor as a Tula Fale—a high talking chief—and they maintain mana, or supernatural power. J) This is a tortoise shell, to deflect evil spirits. Warriors used shells as shields. ([[Read more|http://www.memorylane.tattoo/blog-2133823458/dwayne-johnson-the-rock-tattoos]])<</sidebar>> <<deepdive "https://vugeo.github.io/regional/humaaans/flat assets/Humaaans/sitting-2.png">>Want to keep learning about Samoa? Read more [[here|https://culturalatlas.sbs.com.au/samoan-culture/core-concepts-5d067684-fdc5-423f-93a6-41d1de28911e]] (via [[Cultural Atlas|https://culturalatlas.sbs.com.au/]]).<</deepdive>><<sectionheader "Cultural Adjustment">>Because English is the predominant language in countries like Australia and New Zealand, students often think they will be culturally similar to the US. This can make it seem like cultural adjustment will be super easy--''but the differences between the U.S. and these locations are plentiful and may sneak up on you!'' In fact, because these places are like home, but //not quite//, ''the adjustment process can actually be even more difficult'' than traveling to a country entirely different from your own. In Samoa, for example, you may find that living in a host family may help you understand yourself, your culture, and your identity more strongly. Having an ''open mind'' and ''flexibility'' in the face of cultural differences will help you adapt to your home for the semester. You will have a chance to hear directly from study abroad alumni on how they navigated the cultural adjustment while in the South Pacific at the in-person meeting later this semester. <<sectionheader "What Are Quizzes?">> <img src="https://vugeo.github.io/regional/humaaans/flat assets/Humaaans/standing-25.png" class="action-intro-humaaan aniview" data-av-animation="slideInLeft"> <div class="aniview action-intro-text speech-bubble" data-av-animation="slideInRight"><h2>Hey...</h2>You're about to see your first ''Quiz Question.'' You know yourself best, and you are best-positioned to ensure that you do what you need to do to take care of yourself. That said, we want to be sure you're aware of two important resources that you should rely on if you're having problems. <<button [[Next|Key Resource (1)]]>><</button>><<sectionheader "Health and Safety">> !!!Key Resource #1: Program Staff Your most important resource is ''the staff of your program''. Who are these staff? That depends on your program model: * You are studying through a US organization such as IFSA, SIT, or CIEE: Your program's ''director'' or ''student services coordinator''. * You are studying abroad on an exchange program or directly enrolled in a university: Your ''host university's international office''. Your program staff will be familiar with most aspects of life in your host country. They will be a great first resource to talk about many things, including: * Health issues * Medical resources, including clinics or hospitals * Safety/security protocols and updates * Safe and unsafe areas in your city or other region * Things to do, interesting places to check out, etc. In most cases, you will be able to contact program staff 24/7, so that they can aid you in case of emergency. Be sure to ''enter any emergency numbers you're given into your phone''. <<button [[Next|Key Resource (2)]]>><</button>><<sectionheader "Health and Safety">> !!!Key Resource #2: Vanderbilt Incident Response for Travel Vanderbilt offers its own health and safety support via the Vanderbilt Incident Response for Travel (VIRT) team. VIRT can provide safety-related guidance and assistance for Vanderbilt students and staff. Some of the ways in which VIRT can assist include: * Providing consultation on a range of challenges including mental health, medical, and personal safety concerns to help you make informed decisions * Guiding you in using Vanderbilt-issued insurance * Coordinating a medical or emergency evacuation from abroad If you are in an emergency situation, please call VIRT at +1 615-322-2745. Tell the VU Public Safety dispatcher that you want to report an issue to VIRT. For non-emergencies, email <a href="mailto:VIRT@vanderbilt.edu">VIRT@vanderbilt.edu</a>. Please note that ''VIRT is a mandatory reporter'' for matters related to sexual assault or intimate partner violence. If you are a victim and want a limited confidentiality resource, you may contact [[Project Safe|https://www.vanderbilt.edu/projectsafe/]] 24/7 at +1 615-322-7233. <<sidebar "When to Contact VIRT">> \ Most study abroad students will be able to get more convenient support from their program staff, who are right there on the ground with them. But here are some situations where you might want to contact VIRT: * You are traveling away from your program or outside your host country. * You want help using your Vanderbilt-issued health insurance. * You have privacy concerns about contacting your program staff and prefer to work with Vanderbilt directly. <</sidebar>> <<button [[Next|Save VIRT Contact Info]]>><</button>><<actionitem "VIRT" "Health and Wellness">> Add VIRT contact info to your phone by scanning the QR code, or [[download a contact card|http://vugeo.github.io/regional/VIRT.vcf]] to add to your email. <img style="width:150px;text-align:center;" src="https://vugeo.github.io/regional/images/VIRTqr.png" alt="For emergencies, +1 615-322-2745. For non-emergencies, VIRT@vanderbilt.edu"> <</actionitem>><<sectionheader "Health and Wellness">> When you study abroad, you will be overseas for a significant amount of time. Prepare as well as you can by being ''proactive about your health and special needs''. First, consult with a travel medicine clinic about any ''vaccinations'' that might be advisable. You should do this as soon as possible! [[VU Student Health's Travel Clinic|https://www.vumc.org/student-health/travel-medicine]] is right on campus. Before you leave, meet with your medical, dental, and other care providers for a ''full checkup''. You don’t want to be blindsided by an unnoticed condition when you arrive in your new location. <<sidebar>>\ <<regional>> <</sidebar>> <<button [[Continue|Fill Out Pre-Travel Questionnaire]]>><</button>>South Pacific vaccinations may include: * Hepatitis A & B * Japanese Encephalitis * Rabies * Typhoid Depending on where you’re based and where you travel, you may have some exposure to dengue fever and/or Zika. Both are spread by mosquitoes, and vaccines are not generally available. Talk to the Travel Medicine Clinic about your plans to assess your risk, as well as to understand how you can protect yourself.<<regionCode>>Asia RePDO coming soon. Talk with your current health provider about a ''continuing care plan'' for your time abroad. How will you take care of yourself abroad and get the support and resources you need? If possible, communicate with your program as well. They may be able to help you identify resources abroad. <<button [[Continue|Establish Continuing Care Plan]]>><</button>><<actionitem "CCP" "Care Abroad">> Make an appointment with [[Student Health|https://www.vumc.org/student-health/online-appointments]] or the provider of your choice to discuss your continuing care plan. <</actionitem>><<sectionheader "Health and Wellness">> While you know your history, your program staff does not. In an emergency, you may not be able to relay information that is critical to your care. Please consider ''disclosing any physical or mental health conditions'' to your program. You can use the program’s medical history form, or send an email detailing your history and current care plan. <<sidebar>>If you don't want to reveal personal medical information to your program, Vanderbilt Incident Response for Travel can help: contact <a href="mailto:VIRT@vanderbilt.edu">VIRT@vanderbilt.edu</a>.<</sidebar>> If you will need ongoing treatment while abroad, be aware that providers overseas may not have immediate availability. Try to ''set up appointments now, before you travel,'' to ensure you have access to a provider when you arrive. Your abroad program’s staff can help you locate overseas providers, or you can contact GEO. <<button [[Continue|Health Insurance]]>><</button>><<sectionheader "Health and Wellness">> !!Health Insurance A key preparation for a safe study abroad experience is appropriate medical insurance. Vanderbilt will ''automatically enroll'' you in Vanderbilt’s international health insurance. This plan is more comprehensive than most plans and includes coverage for mandatory evacuation, pre existing conditions, and mental health and substance abuse treatment. Before you travel, you will receive an email from Vanderbilt’s international health insurance provider, GeoBlue, with a letter and an insurance card that you can ''print and carry with you''. <<button [[Next|Health Insurance (2)]]>><</button>><<sectionheader "Health and Wellness">> !!Medications Medication is important, and it’s also ''highly-regulated''. Some medications that are available in the US are restricted in other countries. Be sure you know what you can bring with you and what you can’t. It can also be a pain to transport medication across borders. Even if you take only over-the-counter medications, you should be aware that they may be called by different names overseas. Over-the-counter medications may also be more (or less) restricted overseas. If you take any medications regularly, be sure to read the Deep Dives below. <<sidebar>>It is often easiest to bring enough medication with you for the duration of the program, but it's not always possible. Work with your doctor to figure out how to get the care you need.<</sidebar>> <<deepdive "https://vugeo.github.io/regional/humaaans/flat assets/Humaaans/sitting-2.png">>!!!!Medications: Legal Status and Local Names There are two key pieces of information you need to know about your medications<<linkreplace "...(Read more)" t8n>>. First, the ''legal status of the drug in your host country''. Even some over-the-counter drugs may be restricted abroad, so be sure to consider all the drugs you take. Your doctor should be able to help you understand the legal status of your drugs abroad. But you can also contact your host country's embassy here in the US to find out if any of your medications are restricted or banned. The US Department of State provides a [[directory of foreign embassies|https://www.usembassy.gov/]]. The second key thing to know about your medication is the ''generic/chemical name and/or the local brand names'' it goes by abroad. To ''find the generic or chemical name'' of a drug, you can check the National Institutes of Health’s [[MedlinePlus website|http://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/druginformation.html]]. It may be somewhat trickier to find out the brand name the drug might be sold under in your host country. [[This tool|https://members.geobluestudents.com/TranslationTools/DrugEquivalents]] from Vanderbilt’s international health insurance provider will often be useful.<</linkreplace>> !!!!Medications: Transporting Medications If possible, ''take enough medicine with you to cover your entire stay abroad''<<linkreplace "...(Read more)" t8n>>. Discuss with your physician and program staff how you will get enough medication for your stay. Please be aware that mailing of drugs overseas is [[heavily regulated|https://pe.usps.com/text/pub52/pub52c4_019.htm#ep290406]]. Whatever the legal status of your medications, ''request a letter from your physician'' explaining why the drugs you are transporting have been prescribed to you. Also include over-the-counter drugs if needed. You will want to take this letter with you //whenever you travel!// Request that your doctor use the local brand names or generic/chemical names for your drugs in the letter. <<resources>> [[MedlinePlus|http://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/druginformation.html]], information on prescription and over-the-counter drugs, including generic/chemical names [[GeoBlue Drug Translation Guide|https://members.geobluestudents.com/TranslationTools/DrugEquivalents]], offers equivalent brand names and availability for frequently visited countries/destinations [[Directory of Foreign Embassies|https://www.usembassy.gov/]], US Department of State [[USPS Regulations for Mailing of Controlled Substances|https://pe.usps.com/text/pub52/pub52c4_019.htm#ep290406]] [[Traveler’s Checklist|http://travel.state.gov/content/passports/english/go/checklist.html]] from the US Department of State [[The Yellow Book|http://wwwnc.cdc.gov/travel/yellowbook/2014/table-of-contents]], the CDC’s extensive guide for foreign travel, with answers to questions you didn’t even know to ask!<</resources>><</linkreplace>><</deepdive>> <<button [[Continue|Special Considerations]]>><</button>><<sectionheader "Health and Wellness">> !!Special Considerations If you have registered with the [[Office of Student Access Services|https://www.vanderbilt.edu/student-access/]] to receive accommodations at Vanderbilt, you will want to learn whether you can get similar accommodations on your program abroad. Here's the general answer: Most requests can be honored abroad. But, laws in other countries often differ from what is mandated by US law, and ''not all requests can be met exactly''. To [[get started|https://www.vanderbilt.edu/student-access/disability/#study_abroad]], consult with Student Access Services staff. Request that they send your accommodations letter to your program advisor or on-site staff. ''Do this //before// you depart!'' Program staff will use this letter in researching what accommodations are possible on site. If you have a challenge that you have so far managed without working with Student Access Services, you may want to meet with them before you study abroad. In addition to providing you with a letter, they can help you think through what you might need to ask of your program staff abroad. <<resources>> [[Office of Student Access Services|https://www.vanderbilt.edu/student-access/]] [[Mobility International USA|http://www.miusa.org/]], resources for travelers with disabilities [[Travelers with Disabilities|http://wwwnc.cdc.gov/travel/yellowbook/2014/chapter-8-advising-travelers-with-specific-needs/travelers-with-disabilities]], excellent information on traveling with physical disabilities<</resources>> <<button [[Continue|Health and Wellness Quiz 1a]]>><</button>><<question "Overseas, I can expect to find any medication I have access to in the US with minimal effort.">>\ \ <<if $HealthWell1 is "complete">>\ <<sidebar>>You have already completed this section of questions! In fact, some American cities have higher rates of violent crime than most of the countries where Vanderbilt sends students. But when you go abroad, you will be in an unfamiliar place, some of the hazards may be a bit different, and you will leave most of your usual support structure behind. So we want to focus on safety a bit to ensure that you are prepared. We’ve already covered who your most important health and safety resources abroad will be. In the pages that follow, we will introduce you to some of the other key things you need to know. But don’t forget that ''you are the primary guarantor of your own safety''. <<button [[Next|Personal Safety]]>><</button>><<sectionheader "Safety and Security">> !!Personal Safety ''Crime happens.'' Everywhere in the world. In most of the South Pacific, the crime rate is relatively low, but petty crime is not uncommon in areas frequented by tourists. Scammers and thieves may perceive foreigners as distracted or less knowledgeable, and therefore an easy target. ''To lower your personal risk, follow these key guidelines'': * Travel in groups, especially at night. * When you are in public, pay attention to your surroundings. Don’t wear headphones or give the impression that you are distracted. * Avoid dimly lit areas and alleys or other shortcuts. * Keep a low profile. Avoid loud conversations or public arguments. * Always lock the door to your hotel, apartment, or dorm room. * Dress modestly and avoid carrying or flashing large amounts of cash. * The opportunity for more significant crimes, such as harassment and assault, is increased with alcohol consumption. <<sidebar>><img style="float:right;height:36px;" src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/2/2f/Beating_Heart.gif">Did you know that in Samoa, it’s an actual crime to forget your wife’s birthday?<</sidebar>><<sectionheader "Safety and Security">> Educate yourself about some of the kinds of petty crime you might be exposed to, as well as ways to prevent them. Here are some videos to get you started: !!!Seven Simple Ways Pickpockets Take Advantage of You <iframe width="560" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/eLTSarCuoeo" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture" allowfullscreen></iframe> !!!How to Avoid a Taxi Scam <iframe width="560" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/b1MHuW00BuQ" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture" allowfullscreen></iframe> !!!How Does ATM Skimming Work? <iframe width="560" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/EhgkuVneHgM" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture" allowfullscreen></iframe> <<button [[Next|Alcohol and Drugs]]>><</button>><<sectionheader "Safety and Security">> !!Alcohol consumption On all study abroad programs, ''alcohol is a major contributing factor'' to all types of incidents, whether injury, illness, sexual assault, etc. Irresponsible alcohol consumption, especially in an unfamiliar cultural context, can be risky. If you choose to consume alcohol abroad, keep in mind the local cultural expectations around alcohol. <<regional>>\ <<button [[Next|Alcohol and Drugs (2)]]>><</button>><<sectionheader "Safety and Security">> !!!Independent Travel and Activities Your program may offer some opportunities for travel or other organized activities, but it is also very likely that you will seek out your own activities and travel. Regardless of whether you do so with friends on your own, please remember that ''you are responsible for ensuring your own safety when you undertake independent activities''. Take the time to ''research destinations'' and to understand potential safety issues. Printed guidebooks can often be a good source of safety information, and the internet and social media are other potential avenues. <<regional>> <<button[[Next|Sharing Your Travel Plans]]>><</button>> <<sectionheader "Safety and Security">> !!!Sharing Your Travel Plans During a major crisis such as political turmoil or a natural disaster, <span class="tooltip">VIRT<span class="tooltiptext">Vanderbilt Incident Response for Travel</span></span> will partner with your program to verify your safety and assist you proactively. To do this effectively, the VIRT team needs to know where you are. Your study abroad destination is shared with VIRT automatically, but when you travel on your own or with friends, you need to ''proactively share your itinerary''. <<button[[Next|Communication]]>><</button>><<sectionheader "Safety and Security">> !!!Communication Going AWOL on a study abroad program is ''not cool''. You need to have at least ''one reliable method of contact while abroad''. Your options are getting a local phone, using a local SIM card for an unlocked phone (call your cell service to unlock your phone), or signing up for an international phone plan with your current cell provider. Your program may have specific requirements. Be sure to research your options before you depart--[[program alumni|https://www.vanderbilt.edu/geo/advising/#alumni]] are always helpful in deciding which option may be best! ''Carry a hard copy of local emergency numbers and important contact numbers'' (your host family, resident director, roommate, etc.). This will be useful if you lose your phone or need to use a phone other than your own. When contacted by your program, by VIRT, or by GEO in an emergency, ''always respond immediately''. If you don’t, our next call will be to your family or other designated emergency contact. Your program provider may ask you to log your independent travel while on-site. Students on exchange programs should follow host university travel requirements. <<button[[Next|In Case of Emergency]]>><</button>><<sectionheader "Safety and Security">> !!!In Case of Emergency The most important thing you can do to prepare for an emergency is know who to contact and to be able to do so immediately. If you are not in immediate danger, your first contact will usually be your ''program staff'', such as your resident director or international office staff. Be sure to know who these folks are and enter their contact info into your phone. ''If program staff is not immediately available, try to get in touch with <span class="tooltip">VIRT<span class="tooltiptext">Vanderbilt Incident Response for Travel</span></span> before contacting law enforcement.'' Why? Laws and attitudes vary across the world, and engaging with law enforcement abroad can be a complicated cross-cultural experience. In some countries and in some cases, reporting a crime may also create legal jeopardy for the victim. Familiarize yourself with the cultural context of your host country as much as possible, but make use of your program staff and VIRT to help you navigate interactions with law enforcement. In the event that you are arrested overseas, contact your program staff and/or VIRT. <<button [[Next|In Case of Emergency (2)]]>><</button>><<actionitem "911" "Sexual Misconduct">> Enter the local 911 equivalents for countries you will be visiting into your phone’s address book. You may also want to write them down. Note that different emergency services might have different numbers, so include them all. [[State Deparment list|https://travel.state.gov/content/dam/students-abroad/pdfs/911_ABROAD.pdf]] [[Wikipedia page|https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_emergency_telephone_numbers]] <</actionitem>><<sectionheader "Safety and Security">> Need a study break? Check out this actual police recruitment video from New Zealand! <iframe width="560" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/UDri-PZ4Rz8" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture" allowfullscreen></iframe><<sectionheader "Safety and Security">> !!!Sexual Misconduct If you are a victim of sexual misconduct while abroad, ''contact the resident director of your program for help''. If you are unable or unwilling to discuss the issue with program staff, please contact [[Vanderbilt Incident Response for Travel (VIRT)|https://www.vanderbilt.edu/virt/]] or [[Project Safe|http://www.vanderbilt.edu/projectsafe/]]. Not all countries offer the same legal protections for victims as are offered in the United States. Again, Vanderbilt can explain your options before you file a formal police report. VIRT is a mandatory reporter for matters related to sexual misconduct and power-based violence. Project Safe has someone available 24/7, 365 days a year, and is a limited confidentiality resource. The Student Handbook’s [[policy on Sexual Misconduct|http://www.vanderbilt.edu/student_handbook/sexual-misconduct/]] identifies confidential resources (see also [[Project Safe|https://www.vanderbilt.edu/projectsafe/wp-content/uploads/sites/133/VU-One-Page-Resources-List_Students_2016-17-final.pdf]]). <<button[[Next|Study Break]]>><</button>><<sectionheader "Safety and Security">> !!!The Role of the Embassy Embassies across the world exist not only to facilitate diplomacy, but also to provide services to their citizens traveling abroad. One of the most important services is ''evacuation in the event of political crisis or natural disaster''. Be sure to register with your home country’s embassy so that they can keep you informed both before and during an emergency. Consular agents at US embassies are also available 24/7 to help US citizens with emergencies. While you have other resources, including your program staff and Vanderbilt Incident Response for Travel (VIRT), you might find the consulate useful as an additional resource. Information on services available through US embassies can be found on [[the State Department's website|https://travel.state.gov/content/travel/en/international-travel/emergencies.html]]. Students abroad are subject to local laws and can be jailed. While embassies can sometimes provide support and services to their incarcerated citizens, they can do very little more than that. If you get into trouble abroad, you will face consequences. <<sidebar>>Here are links to the US embassies in... <<regional>><</sidebar>> ''International students'' should be aware the US Department of State cannot generally provide assistance to citizens of other countries, even those who are enrolled at a US university. However, your home country likely offers similar services. Research your home country embassies’ contact information and services before you travel. <<button[[Next|Register with STEP]]>><</button>><<actionitem "STEP" "Conduct Abroad">> ''Register your travel with your home country’s embassy'' US students: Register with the Department of State’s [[Smart Traveler Enrollment Program|https://step.state.gov/step/]] International students should investigate the resources provided by their home embassy in the countries where they plan to travel. If your country has an equivalent traveler enrollment program, use it. Otherwise, contact the embassy when you arrive in your host country to register your presence. <</actionitem>><<sectionheader "Safety and Security">> !!!Conduct abroad You are subject to your abroad institution’s rules, but you //also// need to abide by Vanderbilt’s conduct policies. The standards of behavior described in the VU [[Student Handbook|http://www.vanderbilt.edu/student_handbook/]] and [[Honor System|http://www.vanderbilt.edu/student_handbook/the-honor-system/]] remain in effect while you are abroad. Conduct that violates these codes ''may result in sanctions when you return to Vanderbilt'', even if you have already received sanctions from your program abroad. Social norms—and civil and criminal laws—vary from country to country. Even so, ''Vanderbilt’s policies'', including the university’s [[Student Accountability|https://www.vanderbilt.edu/student_handbook/student-conduct/]] and [[Sexual Misconduct and Intimate Partner Violence|https://www.vanderbilt.edu/student_handbook/sexual-misconduct/]] policies, ''apply in all study abroad programs'' in which Vanderbilt students participate, whether those programs are administered by Vanderbilt or a third party. You are also (of course) ''subject to local laws'' while you are abroad. Foreign laws and legal systems may be quite different from those in your home country, and you should get to know the key differences. If you break local laws while abroad, neither Vanderbilt nor your country’s embassy can get you out of jail, though both may be able to offer some support. If you have legal troubles while abroad, contact both VIRT and your home country’s embassy. If you do get kicked off your program for violating rules, you will be responsible for ''any financial penalty incurred''. It will also have the same consequences for your four-year plan as a dismissal from Vanderbilt--so don’t allow it to happen! <<button[[Check Your Knowledge|Security Quiz 1a]]>><</button>><<question "If I get kicked off my program, I can start classes on campus at Vanderbilt as soon as I get home.">>\ \ <<if $Security1 is "complete">>\ <<sidebar>>You have already completed this section of questions! ''Preparation is key!'' GEO recommends researching your destination country, as well as any additional locations you may visit, online to find helpful information about local weather, currency, time difference, etc.--even cultural hints like tipping! GEO has created ''a list to get you started''; it is not an exhaustive list by any means, but you can use it to start considering the information you need to gather! You can find this checklist [[here|https://geo.vanderbilt.edu/_customtags/ct_FileRetrieve.cfm?File_ID=22612]], or on GEO's [[Identity and Culture page|https://www.vanderbilt.edu/geo/identityresources/]]. <<sidebar>>Can you identify the type of socket you will encounter while you are abroad? <<regional>> <</sidebar>> <<button [[Next|Housing]]>><</button>><<sectionheader "Cultural Adjustment">><h2>Race and Ethnicity</h2> Discourse around race in the US, and in particular on a university campus, looks very different from these conversations in other areas of the world. Most countries in the South Pacific appear very homogenous, so students not of Polynesian or European descent might stand out in their respective locations. ''Think about the implications of homogeneity''--you might have an interaction that could be perceived as a microaggression in the U.S.; often this is not fueled by overt racism but rather by curiosity due to lack of exposure. Stereotypes that exist at home don’t necessarily exist elsewhere. This may require you to ''re-examine the expectations you have'' around your identity and how others perceive you to better understand how your new environment may impact you.<<sectionheader "Cultural Adjustment">> !!LGBTQI Issues in the South Pacific Laws and attitudes towards ''LGBTQI'' rights differ widely across the South Pacific. For example, same-sex acts are illegal in Samoa as well as most of Polynesia, Melanesia, and Indonesia. Gay marriage was legalized in Australia in 2017, and in New Zealand, people identifying as LGBTQI have the same legal rights as non-LGBQTI-identifying people. Even in Australia and New Zealand, acceptance and understanding of LGBTQI issues is uneven across the country, with cities usually more open and accepting than rural areas. For instance, Sydney's Gay and Lesbian Mardi Gras Festival is one of the largest pride parades in the world. Everyone gets in on the festivities, including the government, local businesses, and even [[banks|https://www.youtube.com/watch?time_continue=30&v=SWDW114cji8]]. Just like in the U.S., anti-LGBTQ discrimination and even violence are unfortunately not unknown in the South Pacific. ''We advise you to observe your surroundings before deciding where and with whom you feel safe being out.'' The staff on your program will usually have an understanding of both the US context and the local context, and we also encourage you to talk with them as you adjust to your new location. <<sidebar "Fa’afafine">>Fa’afafine are people who identify themselves as a third-gender in Samoa, American Samoa and the Samoan society, and some theorize an integral part of traditional Samoan culture. Fa’afafine are male at birth, and explicitly embody both masculine and feminine gender traits, fashioned in a way unique to this part of the world. Traditionally, if a family has more boys than girls or not enough girls to help with women’s duties around the house, male children would be chosen to be raised as fa’afafine. [[It has been estimated that 1-5% of Samoans identify as fa’afafine|https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-37227803]]. [img[https://vugeo.github.io/regional/images/faafafine-assn.jpg]] <span class="attribute"> Now former US Ambassador to New Zealand and Samoa, David Huebner (seated, middle right), meets with leaders of the Samoan Fa'afafine Association in 2011. He says, "Established in 2006, the Association addresses issues faced by gender identity and sexual orientation minorities in Samoa. Fa’afafine occupy a respected place in Samoan culture and society, as evidenced by the fact that Prime Minister Tuila’epa Sa’ilele Malielegaoi serves as the Association’s outside patron." [[Photo|https://www.flickr.com/photos/us_embassy_newzealand/5836989155/in/photostream/]] by [[US Embassy|https://www.flickr.com/photos/us_embassy_newzealand/]] (New Zealand) is licensed under [[CC BY-ND 2.0|https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nd/2.0/]]</span> <</sidebar>> <<resources>> [[Equaldex|http://Equaldex.com/]], LGBT rights in the world [[IGLTA, The International Gay/Lesbian Travel Association|https://www.iglta.org/]] [[GayStay New Zealand|http://www.gaystay.co.nz/]], LGBT-friendly accomodations in New Zealand [[The Star-Observer Online|https://www.diversitynetwork.org/page/Australia_CDN]], premier Australian gay periodical [[LGBTI Travel Information|https://travel.state.gov/content/travel/en/international-travel/before-you-go/travelers-with-special-considerations/lgbti.html]], State Department resources for LGBT travelers [[Utopia|http://www.utopia-asia.com/]], an online guide to Asia-Pacific gay and lesbian resources, including legal and cultural information as well as links to country-specific resources If you have a smart phone and are traveling within the U.S. or Europe, you can download the REFUGE Restroom app to help you locate gender inclusive restrooms.<</resources>> <<sectionheader "Cultural Adjustment">> !!Dietary Preferences Restrictive dietary preferences, including vegan, vegetarian and gluten-free, can be relatively easily accommodated in Australia and New Zealand. Wear your seatbelt! In most of the South Pacific, you’ll (hopefully immediately!) notice that car drive on the left side of the road. Consider this extra motivation to look both ways before crossing the street. \ /*[rental cars]*/\ <<sidebar "Did you know...">>\ In 2009, Samoa [[switched up their roads completely|http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/8243110.stm]]--from driving on the right to driving on the left. This made Samoa the first country since the 1970s to make this kind change in traffic patterns. To ease the transition and minimize vehicle accidents, the government declared a two-day holiday and a three-day ban on alcohol sales!<</sidebar>><<sectionheader "Safety and Security">> ''Earthquakes'' are not uncommon in this region, particularly in New Zealand (which as a result, has very stringent building regulations). Be sure you are primed on [[what to do|https://www.ses.vic.gov.au/get-ready/quakesafe/what-to-do-in-an-earthquake]] in the event of one! Tsunamis following an earthquake are also a possibility near the coast. <img style="width:80ch;" src="https://farm5.staticflickr.com/4143/4955151031_3e2a80c774_b.jpg" alt="Earthquake!"> <<attribute "Earthquake!" "https://www.flickr.com/photos/digitalsadhu/4955151031/in/photolist-8xSrLt-e5y8mZ-8yuJdB-8xSraB-8xSr7M-8zraj4-8xSr2a-8yxxzd-9kAGaV-8xVmc1-8xSjqk-9kS3vV-8ybHRz-8GjBXU-a146CA-8ybGK2-8ybxzR-ngbnYs-9kbN2w-9kbRk7-8xVnwA-8zuXvu-8zrMa2-8zrJWZ-nDdeWi-8yuHzr-8zrEGk-fQzX4t-oZziU8-8zrG8X-di4Pgc-e5iRhT-9kobju-8xSjS8-aCUb8D-bBNpfZ-9BVFm8-Db6Wqk-bmyvEE-9kCTYU-8xVoEL-8xSrY2-8xVpf1-dQiV5y-8xSkNr-8xSnnp-p2ggjj-8xSrj6-bXbptK-aCUasZ/" "Richard Walker" "https://www.flickr.com/photos/digitalsadhu/" "CC BY-NC 2.0" "https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/2.0/">>\ Northern and eastern Australia as well as the Pacific islands, including Samoa, are subject to occasionally quite powerful ''tropical cyclones''. Between November and April (cyclone season), be sure to pay attention to television or radio, or subscribe to warning notifications on your cell phone. Know how and where best to shelter.<<sectionheader "Traveling and Living Abroad">> !!Housing While abroad, you will either be living in on-campus residence halls, on-campus student apartments or flats, or in a homestay. Housing can be an ''important part'' of your abroad experience. Be thoughtful about your housing preferences. <<regional>> <<button [[Next|Housing (2)]]>><</button>><<sectionheader "Staying Connected">> The core of studying abroad is about exploring new ways of connecting with the world as well as yourself. As you explore, we encourage you to ''seek balance'': How do you build relationships in your new environment while also maintaining connections back home? How can you stay engaged with your friends and family while being fully present abroad? What tools are available to facilitate both existing and new relationships? <<sidebar>>We surveyed study abroad participants on what they missed the most while abroad. “family and friends” was the top answer, “food” was a close second. Guess what--students also find that they miss friends and food from abroad the most when they return home!<</sidebar>> <<button [[Next|Local Community]]>><</button>><<sectionheader "Staying Connected">> !!Connect with Local Community Think about the kinds of experiences that you want while you are abroad. How will you connect with local culture and community? Having a plan, whether to connect through your host family, with a local roommate, or by joining a local sports team, will help you jumpstart the adjustment process once you arrive. <div class="quote">//The biggest perk of the study abroad program was meeting people from all over the world. I realized that there is a big world out there filled with cool people that I want to get to know.// -- Study Abroad Alum</div> <div class="quote">//Volunteering somewhere in the community, if you have the chance, is an incredible experience that you shouldn't miss out on. It helps immerse you in the culture while giving back to the community and learn more about the place you're living in.// -- Study Abroad Alum</div> <<button [[Next|Connect Home]]>><</button>><<sectionheader "Staying Connected">> !!Connect with Home It’s also important to have a plan about staying connected back home. Whether with family, friends, or a significant other, ''set clear expectations'' about how and when you’ll be able to communicate. In fact, many students commented that staying connected with family and friends back home was what got them through times of loneliness while abroad. Remember that ''you probably won’t have as much access to internet'' as you do at Vanderbilt. <<button [[Next|Connect VU]]>><</button>><<sectionheader "Staying Connected">> !!Connect with VU You’ll need to stay connected to Vanderbilt, at least a little bit! ''Keep up with your Vanderbilt email''; that will be the primary method for GEO as well as other departments on campus to contact you. Keep an account of your experiences abroad so that you can share your reflections with the VU community when you return. <<sidebar>>One fun way to share your experience is the ''GEO Photo Contest''! Take plenty of photos while abroad – they could end up appearing on Vanderbilt social media, posted around campus, or included in GEO publications and website. Keep an eye out for contest details the end of your semester.<</sidebar>> <<button [[Next|Connect VU 2]]>><</button>><<sectionheader "Recommended Readings & Media">> !!!Australia [[In a Sun-Burned Country|https://www.amazon.com/Sunburned-Country-Bill-Bryson/dp/0767903862/ref=sr_1_1?s=books&ie=UTF8&qid=1493238780&sr=1-1&keywords=bill+bryson+in+a+sunburned+country]], by Bill Bryson [[Shadow Child: A Memoir of the Stolen Generation|https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/453570.Shadow_Child]], by Rosalie Fraser [[The Fatal Shore: The Epic of Australia's Founding|https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/306090.The_Fatal_Shore]], by Robert Hughes [[Carpentaria|https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/633484.Carpentaria]], by Alexis Wright [[Cloudstreet|https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/343881.Cloudstreet]], by Tim Winton [[Secret City|https://www.imdb.com/title/tt4976512/]] (TV, 2016-2018) [[Rabbit-Proof Fence|https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0252444/]] (2002) !!!New Zealand [[A Traveller's History of New Zealand and the South Pacific Islands|https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/559503.A_Traveller_s_History_of_New_Zealand_and_the_South_Pacific_Islands]] [[Top of the Lake|https://www.imdb.com/title/tt2103085/]] (TV, 2013-) [[The Piano|https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0107822/?ref_=nv_sr_1]] (1994) [[Heavenly Creatures|https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0110005/?ref_=nv_sr_1]] (1994) !!!Samoa and Polynesia [[Leaves of the Banyan Tree|https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/368553.Leaves_of_the_Banyan_Tree]], by Albert Wendt [[My Samoan Chief|https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/1592618.My_Samoan_Chief]], by Fay G. Instructions for submitting courses can be found [[here|https://forms.vanderbilt.edu/view.php?id=344828]]. Evaluations in YES are active for ''five years'' and apply to all students who take the course. You ''cannot request another review'' of a course on the list unless it will expire before you go abroad. <<sidebar>>Important: the YES Study Abroad Course Search Tool only shows courses Vanderbilt students have already taken abroad. It is not a full list of available courses!<</sidebar>> In the following pages, we’ll show you how to read the YES Study Abroad Course Search Tool. One ''additional'' credit hour will count as FNEC-2050 FNEC Elective. <<button [[Next|How to Read Tool (2)]]>><</button>><<sectionheader "Academic Policies">> !!The Most Important Thing to Know About Course Review ''If you have courses that are not already on the YES tool, get them evaluated as early as possible.'' Don’t leave it until the last minute. Why? *You don't want to commit to a class without knowing whether you will receive Vanderbilt credit! *The Registrar can't record your credit back at Vanderbilt until all your courses have been reviewed. This can be a great source of anxiety! Here are some of the things an incomplete transcript can stop you from doing: **Registering for upper-level courses **Completing internship requirements **Applying for medical or law school **Applying for scholarships <<button[[Next|Tips Course Review]]>><</button>> <<sectionheader "Academic Policies">> !!Tips for Successful Course Review *Remember that Vanderbilt faculty determine the number of credits a course will earn. ''You must check the course evaluation via YES to confirm'' how many credits you’ll get--or whether the course will get any Vanderbilt credit at all. *If you’re on a semester-long program and the total credits you earn abroad amounts to fewer than 12 VU credits, ''you will be placed on academic probation'', and your financial aid eligibility may be in jeopardy. *Find a ''complete syllabus'' to submit for review. A short course description is not enough for faculty evaluation. *Only submit courses that you’re ''actually interested'' in taking for evaluation. *If you want a course to ''count toward your major or minor differently'' than is listed on YES, your next step will depend on your college: **//Blair School of Music//: Contact Blair’s [[Office of Academic Services|https://blair.vanderbilt.edu/academics/]]. **//College of Arts and Science//: Contact the departmental Director of Undergraduate Studies for the major or minor you want the course to count toward. **//Peabody College//: Contact [[Peabody’s Office of Academic Services|https://peabody.vanderbilt.edu/admin-offices/oas/index.php]]. **//Vanderbilt School of Engineering//: Contact [[VUSE’s Office of Academic Services|https://engineering.vanderbilt.edu/academic-services/]]. <<deepdive "https://vugeo.github.io/regional/humaaans/flat assets/Humaaans/sitting-2.png">>!!!!What if I can’t find a full syllabus for evaluation? In order for your abroad course to be evaluated by Vanderbilt faculty, ''the following information is required'': <<linkreplace "(Read more)" t8n>> *Course name *Course description *Course hours *Weekly lecture topics *Required readings/supplemental readings *Assignments (including number of essays, length) *Assessment information *Course prerequisites (if relevant) *Lab assignments (if relevant *Other information as requested by the VU Registrar<</linkreplace>><</deepdive>> <<button[[Continue|Academic Policies Quiz 2a]]>><</button>><<sectionheader "Safety and Security">> The legal drinking age in Samoa is the same as in the U.S., 21. In Australia and New Zealand, though, it’s 18, so 21st birthdays are no big deal in the South Pacific. Don’t be the out of control, binge-drinking college student—you’ll be pegged as an American right away! Also, hopefully we don’t have to tell you this, but ''don’t do drugs''. Putting aside the legal ramifications of committing a crime in a country where you aren’t a citizen, it is an easy way to get kicked out of your program faster than you can say ‘cheers, mate.’ Don’t forget, you are still responsible to the Vanderbilt code of conduct; the VU alcohol policy specifies that you are subject to local regulations. ([[VU Student Handbook|https://www.vanderbilt.edu/student_handbook/]]) <div class="quote">//Be safe when going out and drinking, especially people who are not legally allowed to drink in the United States. Don't use your time abroad to test your limits.// – Spring 2018 Study Abroad Alum</div> <<sidebar>>[[Penalties|http://www.police.govt.nz/advice/drugs-and-alcohol/illicit-drugs-offences-and-penalties]] for possession and use of even small amounts of illegal drugs in New Zealand may include long jail sentences and heavy fines.<</sidebar>><<if $region is "The South Pacific">> Your region is $region. Pay close attention to the instructions and tips your program staff gives you to ensure a successful homestay experience. Be sure to include ''all pertinent information'' on your housing form, such as dietary restrictions, sensitivities, personal identities or other considerations, so your program staff can place you with the best-fit host family. No matter what, be prepared to ''be flexible''! <<deepdive "https://vugeo.github.io/regional/humaaans/flat assets/Humaaans/sitting-2.png">>!!!!Gifts and Relationships Presenting a gift shows that you value a relationship—even a new one. <<linkreplace "(Read more)" t8n>>Consider a gift to start off your more important relationships abroad, such as with your homestay family or a host-country roommate. In a cross-cultural setting, the best gifts can be those that let you bring a little of where you’re from to the relationship. Examples might include a Vanderbilt mug or pendant, a photo book about Nashville or your hometown, maple syrup if you’re from Vermont, or maybe biscuit or grits mix if you’re from the South. Not only are gifts like these polite, positive, well-meaning gestures, they can also spur conversations ("Is an American biscuit the same thing as a scone?"). Photos of home are another great conversation starter. Make sure you bring along some photos of your family, your house, your campus, your hobbies, and so on. It’s a great way for people to feel like they are getting to know you and where you come from.<</linkreplace>><</deepdive>> If you have an accommodation registered with Student Access Services, talk with them ASAP to [[get an accomodation letter sent to your program|https://www.vanderbilt.edu/student-access/disability/#study_abroad]]. <<button [[Next|Review VU Study Abroad Housing Policy]]>><</button>><<actionitem "housing" "Staying Connected">> Review Vanderbilt's [[Study Abroad Housing Policy|https://www.vanderbilt.edu/geo/advising/policies/#housing]]. <</actionitem>><<sectionheader "Staying Connected">> !!Connect with VU While abroad, you can also be intentional about ''career development'', whether you are directly participating in an internship or gaining skills from your abroad experience that can contribute to your career path. Here are some tips and pointers: *[[Career Center resources|https://www.vanderbilt.edu/geo/project/study-abroad-and-your-career-search/]] are available to you while abroad *While abroad, you may want to make connections with Vanderbilt alumni who work in countries you are visiting. *Use www.vuconnect.com and www.linkedin.com to see if there are any alumni in the area. **MyVUconnect > Career Adviser Network > Search Alumni Career Advisers *Be intentional about how you spend your time abroad, reflect on your experience regularly--and research how you can leverage your abroad experience to enhance employability. ''You’ll have the opportunity to consider this in-depth during the in-person regional meeting for $region''. You’ll hear study abroad alumni share experiences about developing relationships, adjusting to local culture, becoming open-minded and resilient, staying safe, and other stories that may guide you to create a meaningful semester abroad. <<button [[Next|Recommended Readings & Media]]>><</button>><<sectionheader "Health and Wellness">> !!Mental Health and Well-being Study Abroad can be a wonderful experience as well as a challenging one when it comes to your mental health and well-being. ''It’s a time when previously unknown conditions may surface and pre-existing conditions can be exacerbated.'' If you have a relationship with a ''UCC professional'', speak with them about your plans to study abroad and any necessary steps they would recommend for a care plan while you are away. Consult with ''GEO Safety & Security Manager'' to understand how international insurance cover appointments and prescriptions you may require abroad. In some cases, appointments need to be set up well ''in advance'' to avoid long wait time. If you are on medication, talk with your provider about having a prescription that will last the duration of your program. <<button [[Continue|Continuing Care Plan]]>><</button>><<include $region>><<undefined>> /* this page pulls content from region intro pages.
