A complicated history exists in Australia and New Zealand related to ''Aboriginal'' and ''Maori populations'', respectively, and both communities are still very much grappling with issues of representation, equality, and preservation of their unique cultural heritages. In New Zealand, you can expect to see almost as much Maori language as you do English. You will often be greeted in the [[Maori way|https://www.nytimes.com/2018/09/16/world/asia/new-zealand-maori-language.html#click=https://t.co/hdZdx1RFFg]], kia ora, and you will surely hear all about the ''haka'' (if you haven’t already). <iframe width="560" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/QUbx-AcDgXo" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture" allowfullscreen></iframe> In Australia, you may see an Acknowledgement of Country in email signatures, news reports, and sports matches like Australian Rules Football. <iframe width="560" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/xdI9-RTL_ko" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture" allowfullscreen></iframe> These topics and experiences are worth learning more about during your time abroad to develop an ''awareness'' and ''understanding'' of your program’s location and culture beyond that of a passing tourist. <<resources>> GEO's [[Identity and Culture Resources|https://www.vanderbilt.edu/geo/identityresources/]]<</resources>><<sectionheader "Academic Policies">> !!How to Read the YES Study Abroad Course Search Tool <img id="clickToExp" src="http://vugeo.github.io/regional/images/course search/stochastic-processes-no-equiv.png"><<clickToExp>> The STAT-3011 course at University of Sydney does not have a direct equivalent here at Vanderbilt, but it does receive 4 hours toward graduation requirements. <<button[[Next|Most Important Course Review]]>><</button>><<sectionheader "Academic Policies">> !!How to Read the YES Study Abroad Course Search Tool <img id="clickToExp" src="http://vugeo.github.io/regional/images/course search/biomed-product-development-gnel-nocr.png"><<clickToExp>> Hopefully this goes without saying, but if a course is listed as GNEL-NOCR No Credit at Vanderbilt- ''you will not receive any VU credit nor hours'' if you take it- so don’t! <<button [[Next|How to Read Tool (4)]]>><</button>><<sectionheader "Academic Policies">> !!How to Read the YES Study Abroad Course Search Tool <img id="clickToExp" src="http://vugeo.github.io/regional/images/course search/applied-biomed-engineering-bme-elective.png"><<clickToExp>> When courses don’t have a direct equivalent here at Vanderbilt, the courses show up as Non-Equivalent Credit, like the Applied Biomedical Engineering University of Sydney course above. In this case, defer to the parenthetical to get more information about how this course will be reflected on your degree audit. ''"Non-equivalent credit" is not the same as receiving "no credit."'' Check out the [[Registrar's glossary|https://registrar.vanderbilt.edu/study-abroad/#Glossary]] to understand the terminology. <<button [[Next|How to Read Tool (3)]]>><</button>><<sectionheader "Academic Policies">> !!Vanderbilt Registration For semester-long programs, the placeholder course will be ''0 hours''. The actual number of credits you earn will be reflected on YES after Vanderbilt receives your abroad transcript. For summer courses, GEO will register you for the minimum number of hours your program requires. ''If you take extra summer hours above the placeholder, Student Accounts will bill you for the difference''. This billing will occur after your transcript posts to your Vanderbilt record. <<button [[Next|Registration (3)]]>><</button>><<sectionheader "Academic Policies">> !!Vanderbilt Registration Typically, GEO registers students into their placeholder courses for each term according to the following schedule: Fall: mid-July Spring: mid-November Summer: late May <<button[[Continue|Transcripts]]>><</button>><<sectionheader "Fees, Cost, and Billing">> !!!How do billing and financial aid work? The billing works the same as if you were on-campus. Vanderbilt Student Accounts will bill you on the same billing timeline as if you were on campus. They will issue both e-bills and paper bills, as usual, and payment terms will be the same (including installment plans). Financial aid will post to your account at about the same time as it would if you were on campus. ''Keep in mind that if you are studying abroad in the fall in the southern hemisphere, you may begin school in July but you will not receive any financial aid refund (if applicable) until September.'' If you need an advance on your financial aid for out-of-pocket purchases, please consult your [[Financial Aid Advisor|https://www.vanderbilt.edu/financialaid/undergraduate/index.php]]. ''Remember: Your financial aid travels with you, and your aid package may be [[adjusted|https://forms.vanderbilt.edu/view.php?id=840651]] to meet any increased financial need.'' <<button [[Next|Fees, Cost, and Billing (3)]] >><</button>><<sectionheader "Fees, Cost, and Billing">> There are some situations where your program might also bill you directly. Here’s how that works: *If you are placed into higher-cost housing or board options, such as a residence hall with a required meal plan, your study abroad program will usually bill you directly for those supplemental fees. *If you are on an exchange program, you are responsible for housing and fees and will generally pay those directly to the program, or to third parties. *You might pay your program directly for optional excursions. *You might also have to pay a cleaning or repair fee, for example if you damage your housing or don’t clean it adequately. If you owe money to your program for any reason, ''they may withhold your transcript until you pay''. If your transcript is being held, you will need to work with and pay your program directly to get the transcript released. Vanderbilt cannot do this for you. <<button [[Continue|Find Program Budget Sheet]]>><</button>><<sectionheader "Health and Wellness">> !!Health Insurance International health insurance usually ''only covers you for the official dates of your program.'' If you are planning to travel before or after your program begins, GEO recommends that you purchase additional short-term coverage available through GeoBlue. However, you are free to select any provider. If you are currently under medical care, your international health insurance company can help you locate an appropriate care provider in your host country. ''Plan ahead!'' If you know you want to continue care overseas, contact your international insurer //before// you leave the US. If you need additional help, contact VIRT at <a href="mailto:virt@vanderbilt.edu">VIRT@vanderbilt.edu</a>. <<button [[Next|Health Insurance (3)]]>><</button>><<sectionheader "Health and Wellness">> !!Health Insurance <<resources>> How to Use [[International Insurance|https://www.vanderbilt.edu//global/health-safety/]] Contact VIRT on a non-emergency basis at <a href=”mailto:virt@vanderbilt.edu”>virt@vanderbilt.edu</a> to inquire about using Vanderbilt’s international health insurance to access medical services. Brief description of Vanderbilt’s [[international health insurer’s coverage and services|https://geo.vanderbilt.edu/_customtags/ct_FileRetrieve.cfm?File_ID=2361]]. [[Detailed description of coverage|https://geo.vanderbilt.edu/_customtags/ct_FileRetrieve.cfm?File_ID=15554]] for Vanderbilt’s international health insurer. A brief [[guide to medical care and insurance|http://www.studentsabroad.com/handbook/medical-care-and-insurance.php?country=General]] from StudentsAbroad.com. <</resources>> <<button [[Continue|Medications]]>><</button>> <<regional>> <<button [[Next|Natural Disasters]]>><</button>><<regional>> <<button [[Next|Independent Travel and Activities]]>><</button>>The South Pacific offers many opportunities to participate in ''outdoor adventure activities''. These activities are inherently risky, so you need to make careful judgments about the risks involved. Seek information from individual operators about the risks involved, and the safety precautions they take. Risks tend to increase in severe weather and remote locations.<<sectionheader "Safety and Security">> !!!In Case of Emergency However, if you are in immediate danger or need emergency medical attention, you will need to call local emergency services. Emergency services in different countries have different numbers—''911 doesn’t work abroad''! After you call emergency services, contact your program staff. They understand local protocols and will be able to help you navigate hospitalization, police encounters, and more. If you can’t reach program staff or are traveling where they can’t help you, contact VIRT at +1 615-322-2745. VIRT is available day or night to support you in emergencies. <<sidebar>>If you do need to contact the police while abroad, be sure to request a copy of the police report.<</sidebar>> <<button[[Next|Save Emergency Service Contact Info]]>><</button>><<regional>> <<button[[Next|Embassy]]>><</button>>/* copy the contents of this passage to "Security Quiz 1b Answer The South Pacific" */ \ [[New Zealand|https://www.usembassy.gov/new-zealand/]], [[Australia|https://www.usembassy.gov/australia/]], and [[Samoa|https://www.usembassy.gov/samoa/]]. <span id="g"><<link [img[https://vugeo.github.io/regional/images/socket-type-g.png]]>><<script>>UI.alert("Try again!")<</script>><</link>></span> <span id="i"><<link [img[https://vugeo.github.io/regional/images/socket-type-i.png]]>><<removeclass "#socket" "hidden">><<addclass "#g" "fade">> <<addclass "#d" "fade">><</link>></span> <span id="d"><<link [img[https://vugeo.github.io/regional/images/socket-type-d.png]]>><<script>>UI.alert("Try again!")<</script>><</link>></span> <span id="socket" class="hidden"> ''Correct!'' This is called a Type I socket. Find out more about Type I plugs and sockets on the [[International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC)'s helpful website|https://www.iec.ch/worldplugs/typeI.htm]].</span>Residence halls in Australia and New Zealand are ''co-ed'', including bathrooms. If you have any questions or concerns about this cultural difference, speak with your advisor. Many Aussies and Kiwis live at home and commute to school; living on campus can be the easiest way for you to develop these friendships outside of class. Keep in mind that you may not get your top choice housing, so be sure to ''research all options before selecting your second choice''! <<regional>> <<button [[Finish|Bon Voyage]]>><</button>><<regional>> <<button [[Next|LGBTQI Issues]] >><</button>>/* this passage is an exact copy of "Embassy The South Pacific" */ \ [[New Zealand|https://www.usembassy.gov/new-zealand/]], [[Australia|https://www.usembassy.gov/australia/]], and [[Samoa|https://www.usembassy.gov/samoa/]].
